title.children: Wagner fighters allegedly march into Russia, with leader vowing to go 'all the way' against military

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Prigozhin says his actions are not a military coup. But in a series of audio messages, in which the sound of his voice sometimes varies and can not be independently verified, he appears to suggest that his 25,000-strong militia is en route to oust the leadership of the defense ministry in Moscow. "Those who destroyed our lads, who destroyed the lives of many tens of thousands of Russian soldiers, will be punished. I ask that no one offer resistance," he says. "There are 25,000 of us and we are going to figure out why chaos is happening in the country," he said, promising to tackle any checkpoints or air forces that got in Wagner's way. "We will consider anyone who tries to resist a threat and quickly destroy them."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: The Wagner Group boss has vowed to 'punish' Russia's military leadership

children.content: Prigozhin says his actions are not a military coup.

But in a series of audio messages, in which the sound of his voice sometimes varies and can not be independently verified, he appears to suggest that his 25,000-strong militia is en route to oust the leadership of the defense ministry in Moscow.
"Those who destroyed our lads, who destroyed the lives of many tens of thousands of Russian soldiers, will be punished. I ask that no one offer resistance," he says.
"There are 25,000 of us and we are going to figure out why chaos is happening in the country," he said, promising to tackle any checkpoints or air forces that got in Wagner's way.
"We will consider anyone who tries to resist a threat and quickly destroy them."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Hi there, and welcome to this live blog. Here's what we know about the situation right now: Mercenaries from the Russian mercenary group Wagner, which have been supporting Russia's military in Ukraine, have crossed the border into Russia, and are ready to go "all the way" against the countrys troops, Wagner boss Yevgeny Prigozhin says. Wagner fighters are said to have entered the southern Russian city of Rostov. Prigozhin says Wagner troops were greeted by border guards as they moved into the Rostov region and are now driving into the city. He says young conscripts at checkpoints stood back and offered no resistance, adding that his forces "aren't fighting against children". "But we will destroy anyone who stands in our way," he says. "We are moving forward and will go until the end." This all comes after Russia accused Prigozhin of calling for an armed mutiny after he alleged, without providing evidence, that Russia's military leadership had killed a large number of his fighters in air strikes.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Wagner Group's boss says his troops have entered Russia — here's what we know

children.content: Hi there, and welcome to this live blog.
Here's what we know about the situation right now:

Mercenaries from the Russian mercenary group Wagner, which have been supporting Russia's military in Ukraine, have crossed the border into Russia, and are ready to go "all the way" against the countrys troops, Wagner boss Yevgeny Prigozhin says.
Wagner fighters are said to have entered the southern Russian city of
Rostov
Prigozhin says Wagner troops were greeted by border guards as they moved into the Rostov region and are now driving into the city.
He says young conscripts at checkpoints stood back and offered no resistance, adding that his forces "aren't fighting against children".
"But we will destroy anyone who stands in our way," he says. "We are moving forward and will go until the end."
This all comes after
Russia accused Prigozhin of calling for an armed mutiny
after he alleged, without providing evidence, that Russia's military leadership had killed a large number of his fighters in air strikes.
